Wow, you really ran with the criticism! I'm impressed on the turnaround time, to say the least.

Let's see in the article.

As for things that don't work as well as they could or areas for possible improvement:

The log progression might work better if  Other Stuff before we get into the recursive testing.
A bunch of people get twitchy when [DATA EXPUNGED] gets tacked on the end of stuff. It's generally agreed to work best as a  either reduce it to just the last one or try to give the reader more information to creep them out.
The recursive inception-style tests were a neat idea, but it needs a little more spit and polish. Through the third recursion, it all works and there's a nice progression of weird - test into here, saying that all media was now tuned to static in the Snakebite world, maybe all reflective surfaces as well?). I'm not sure about the final one, but don't just end it on an expungement, or justify it if you do. Perhaps have the camera come out of the hallway into the restaurant at the finale of the Sopranos right before everything usually goes black, but instead the researchers see [DATA EXPUNGED FOR COGNITOHAZARD]. Cleanup in Aisle 3, the new researchers are barred from doing this, and the old researchers are implied to not be around anymore.
There's an odd spelling error or two and some slightly awkward phrasing here and there. Those can be cleaned up when you have  in a day or so and can decide what gets the message across and what could be clearer.






